                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 6351/2.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum from the French Embassy.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">French Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-05-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 10, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The intended understanding between France and Japan is not yet signed. The object
                    is the territorial statu quo in the extreme East, the equality of treatment of
                    all powers, and the integrity of China. While protecting our interests in
                    Indo-China, nothing but clauses favorable to general peace and the interests of
                    all powers in eastern Asia will be contained in it. Far from having any cause of
                    anxiety in this respect, the United States, to whom we are bound by a tried and
                    faithful friendship, can only approve of it. You can speak in this sense to
                    President Roosevelt.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
